---
import SiteLayout from '../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Teaching Underwater Movement — Jadey"
  description="A concise level design breakdown about teaching underwater movement through space, framing, and controlled pressure."
>
  <article class="article-page section-pad">
    <header class="article-header" data-reveal>
      <a class="back-link" href="/analysis/">← Design notes</a>
      <p class="eyebrow">Level design · Player guidance · 6 min read</p>
      <h1>Teaching underwater movement without another tutorial popup</h1>
      <p class="article-deck">
        A demo breakdown of how safe space, framing, landmarks, and escalating pressure can teach a new movement model through play.
      </p>
      <div class="article-byline"><span>Jadey</span><span>Design note 01</span><span>Demo content</span></div>
    </header>

    <div class="article-layout">
      <aside class="article-toc" data-reveal>
        <p>On this page</p>
        <a href="#problem">The problem</a>
        <a href="#sequence">Teaching sequence</a>
        <a href="#feedback">Feedback loop</a>
        <a href="#takeaway">Takeaway</a>
      </aside>
      <div class="article-body" data-reveal>
        <section id="problem">
          <p class="article-kicker">01 / The problem</p>
          <h2>Three dimensions create three times the uncertainty.</h2>
          <p>
            On land, the floor continuously tells the player where they can stand. Underwater, the player must read depth, orientation, oxygen, and destination at the same time. A text prompt can explain the buttons, but it cannot build spatial confidence.
          </p>
          <blockquote>The level should answer “where can I go?” before it asks “how fast can I get there?”</blockquote>
        </section>

        <figure class="article-diagram" aria-label="Three-stage player teaching diagram">
          <div><span>Safe</span><strong>One visible exit</strong></div>
          <i>→</i>
          <div><span>Test</span><strong>One vertical choice</strong></div>
          <i>→</i>
          <div><span>Remix</span><strong>Route + oxygen</strong></div>
          <figcaption>Progression keeps the verb constant while adding one new decision at a time.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <section id="sequence">
          <p class="article-kicker">02 / Teaching sequence</p>
          <h2>Let the camera discover the verb.</h2>
          <p>
            The entry space starts shallow and calm. The exit sits above the player, framed by a bright structure. Moving toward it naturally asks the player to ascend. The next chamber reverses that relationship and places the route below.
          </p>
          <div class="principle-grid">
            <div><span>01</span><h3>Frame the target</h3><p>Use contrast and silhouette before UI markers.</p></div>
            <div><span>02</span><h3>Protect the first attempt</h3><p>No oxygen failure while learning the axis.</p></div>
            <div><span>03</span><h3>Repeat from a new angle</h3><p>Confirm understanding without repeating the exact room.</p></div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <section id="feedback">
          <p class="article-kicker">03 / Feedback loop</p>
          <h2>Change the space when the player hesitates.</h2>
          <p>
            In a real case study, this section would pair observed playtest behaviour with before-and-after images: where players stopped, what they looked at, and which spatial change reduced hesitation.
          </p>
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Observed behaviour</th><th>Likely cause</th><th>Design response</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Player circles the entrance</td><td>Exit silhouette blends into ruins</td><td>Clear background and add a light rhythm</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Player surfaces too early</td><td>Oxygen reads as immediate danger</td><td>Delay depletion during onboarding</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Player misses the return route</td><td>Landmark only reads from one side</td><td>Give it a distinct vertical profile</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </section>

        <section id="takeaway">
          <p class="article-kicker">04 / Takeaway</p>
          <h2>Teach the model, not only the input.</h2>
          <p>
            Inputs are remembered when the player understands what they enable. A good onboarding space makes the movement rule legible, gives the player a low-risk success, then asks them to reuse it under slightly more pressure.
          </p>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</SiteLayout>
